SIMPLE: musca
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Musca
<hw>Mus"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Muscae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a fly.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of dipterous insects,
including the common house fly, and numerous allied species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Formerly, a large part of the Diptera were included
under the genus <gen>Musca</gen>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A small constellation situated
between the Southern Cross and the Pole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscae volitantes</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[L.,
flying flies.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>Specks or filaments
apparently seen moving or gliding about in the field of vision. Their
appearance is often a symptom of disease of the eye, or of disorder of
the nervous system.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muscadelle</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Muscadel</ent>⟦br⟧
